THE SHAPE
=====================================================================
THE SUMMONS — THE PLAGUE BRINGS THEM HOME: Alfonso's reinfection (Mila's
  mother, the slow Warrens rot) finally BLOOMS, and the party is called back
  to Riften to deal with the plague they unknowingly caused. They return to a
  city they KNOW — Balimund's forge and the gear they invested in, Maven's
  patronage, Hofgrir, the Bee and Barb, the people they have come to love.
  They reconnect; they see the fruits of everything they built. The plague is
  the hook that walks them home — so they are STANDING IN IT when it burns.
  (Plague + fire = COMPOUND: the plague is the summons, the dragons are the
  execution, a quarantine-weakened city is why it cannot hold.)

ESTABLISH THEIR STRENGTH FIRST (the Balrog needs contrast): on the road back
  they REFACE a threat they once feared and it is now a BLOODBATH — roving
  draugr (the Dragon Cult is loose; the timing fits), a horde that would once
  have been a real fight, curbstomped by an AP~12 party of monsters. They
  feel like titans. Hold that feeling for exactly one scene.

THE DEFENSE (the PARTY's — no True Wardens here): the two scouts return and
  strike, and the PARTY drops them — an AP~12 monster-party CAN down a pair
  of dragons now, and that win swells the titan-feeling further. But a mortal
  cannot permanently kill a dragon: only the Dragonborn disperses the soul by
  absorbing it. The party drops the bodies and they DO NOT STAY DOWN — the
  souls do not scatter, and the dragons REVIVE. (The party will not
  understand why. The answer is sitting in their own cart.)

THE ELDER DRAGON = THE BALROG OF MORIA (UNWINNABLE — this IS the point):
  then an ELDER dragon descends — categorically above them, too much damage,
  too smart, too tactical, AP~12 and still ANTS before it. They CANNOT win.
  The only play is to survive and FLEE, powerless, alone — no legendary hero
  covering the retreat this time; just their own helplessness while the city
  is erased behind them. TELEGRAPH the unwinnability so they run, not TPK.
  (Bjorn's speed may flicker to save Mila in the flight — consistent with his
  arc, still read by the table as rejuvenation, never the Dragonborn.)

THE FALL: Godzilla-Minus-One register — catastrophe, not battle. Everyone
  they came to love here burns. The screaming. The helplessness. The first
  major hold ERASED. Dragon Cult clock makes a catastrophic jump. The lesson
  lands in the gut: these dragons are not to be trifled with; they have been
  LUCKY all along.

THE BURIED TRAGEDY (long fuse — DO NOT STATE): only the Dragonborn could
  permanently kill those dragons — and the Dragonborn HID from those exact
  two on the road, then helped DROP them with his own party here, and they
  would not stay dead because no one knew he had to take their souls. Bjorn
  could end the elder by absorbing power he does not know he holds.
  Preventable, and his own hands proved it without a soul at the table
  understanding. Detonate only with the eventual reveal.

